---
/**
 * Phase 3B-2 test harness — visual verification of CaseStudyLayout.
 * Delete this page when Phase 3C's first real case study lands.
 *
 * Note: file has no leading underscore so Astro routes it to /case-study-test.
 * (Astro excludes _-prefixed pages from routing; spec used underscore as a
 * naming convention only — deviation accepted, documented in phase-3b-2.md.)
 */
import CaseStudyLayout from '../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';
import SectionHeading from '../components/SectionHeading.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import InlineImage from '../components/InlineImage.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'context',  label: 'Context' },
  { id: 'research', label: 'Research' },
  { id: 'design',   label: 'Design' },
  { id: 'outcomes', label: 'Outcomes' },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="Test Case Study Template"
  description="Visual verification of the Phase 3B-2 case study template scaffolding."
  heroImage={{
    src: '/assets/images/work/non-profit/checa-hero.png',
    alt: 'Laptop displaying a website — placeholder hero image for template testing',
  }}
  meta={{
    company: 'Test Co',
    team: 'Solo',
    role: 'Researcher & Designer',
    timeline: '2024–2025',
  }}
  sections={sections}
>

  <!-- ── SECTION 1: Context ──────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="context" data-title="Context" data-index="1">
    <SectionHeading number="01" title="Context" id="context" />

    <p>Every project begins with a question that matters more than the one originally asked. This case study explores how that reframing process works in practice — from the initial brief through to the decisions that shaped what was ultimately built and why.</p>

    <p>The client came in with a solution in mind. The research team's job was to figure out whether that solution addressed the actual problem, and if not, to surface the real one. This tension between assumed and discovered need is the central thread of this work.</p>

    <InlineImage
      src="/assets/images/work/non-profit/asociacion-personas.png"
      alt="Personas diagram showing two primary user archetypes identified during contextual research"
      label="Context artifact"
      caption="Two primary user archetypes identified during contextual research and validated across interviews."
    />

    <PullQuote
      quote="The question on the brief was never the question that needed answering. Getting to the real one took three weeks of listening."
      variant="teal"
    />

    <p>Setting the right scope early saved considerable effort downstream. Teams that skip this step often build the right solution to the wrong problem — technically correct, behaviourally irrelevant.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 2: Research ─────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="research" data-title="Research" data-index="2">
    <SectionHeading number="02" title="Research" id="research" />

    <p>The research approach combined diary studies with contextual interviews, covering eight participants over a four-week period. The goal was not to validate a hypothesis but to develop one — to understand the shape of the problem before proposing any shape of solution.</p>

    <p>What emerged was a pattern that had been invisible at the organisational level: users were compensating for a system gap with workarounds so habitual they had stopped noticing them. The workarounds were the signal. The system gap was the finding.</p>

    <PullQuote
      quote="Compensation behaviours are the most honest data in UX research. Users will tell you what they wish were true. Their workarounds tell you what actually is."
      attribution="Field notes, week two"
      variant="rose"
    />

    <InlineImage
      src="/assets/images/work/non-profit/checa-hero.png"
      alt="Screenshot of research synthesis board with affinity clusters and emerging themes"
      label="Research synthesis"
      caption="Affinity clustering across interview transcripts — three primary themes emerged from 140+ discrete observations."
    />

    <p>Secondary analysis of support ticket data corroborated the interview findings: the three highest-volume support categories mapped precisely to the three workaround types observed in the field. This triangulation gave the team high confidence in the direction before committing to design exploration.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 3: Design ───────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="design" data-title="Design" data-index="3">
    <SectionHeading number="03" title="Design" id="design" />

    <p>Design exploration began with constraint mapping — not with wireframes. Understanding what could not change (technical architecture, regulatory boundaries, existing workflows) sharpened the space for what could. Constraints, properly understood, are a design resource.</p>

    <p>Three concepts were developed and tested in rapid succession. The first failed in moderated testing within 20 minutes: participants couldn't locate the primary action. The second performed better but introduced a new cognitive load at a critical moment in the flow. The third — a significant simplification of the second — tested cleanly across all five participants.</p>

    <InlineImage
      src="/assets/images/work/non-profit/asociacion-personas.png"
      alt="Three design concepts side by side showing the progression from complex to simplified interface"
      label="Design iterations"
      caption="Three concepts tested in order. Concept C emerged from removing, not adding — a pattern that appeared again in the outcomes."
    />

    <p>The testing process was as important as the designs themselves. Seeing where participants hesitated, where they looked before clicking, where they abandoned and started over — this observational layer told a different story than the think-aloud commentary, and it was the more reliable one.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 4: Outcomes ─────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="outcomes" data-title="Outcomes" data-index="4">
    <SectionHeading number="04" title="Outcomes" id="outcomes" />

    <p>The delivered design addressed the three workaround types identified in research. Post-launch data at the 90-day mark showed a 34% reduction in the support ticket categories that had originally surfaced the problem. The pattern held across user segments.</p>

    <p>More durable than the metrics was the organisational learning. The process demonstrated, in a way that stakeholders could see and follow, how evidence moves from observation to decision. That transparency became a template for subsequent projects on the same team.</p>

    <InlineImage
      src="/assets/images/work/non-profit/checa-hero.png"
      alt="Dashboard showing post-launch support ticket data over 90 days with downward trend in target categories"
      label="Impact data"
      caption="Support ticket volume in the three target categories. 90-day window post-launch."
    />

    <p>Looking back, the most significant decision was the earliest one: resisting the pressure to start designing before the research was complete. That patience, uncomfortable as it was at the time, is what made the outcome legible enough to be acted upon.</p>
  </section>

</CaseStudyLayout>
